2. What does diversity and equity mean to you? How do you promote equity and inclusion when working with data?
 - Equity is understanding that as individuals the requirements to provide the same opportunity to one person as another does not mean they need equal things. 
  There was a cool cartoon I saw a while ago of three people standing one tall one medium height and one short and each wanted to see over the fence.  Equality is where everyone had
  the same size box, but equity was where everyone was able to see over the fence.   As an economist by study and analyst by profession I have found that data is the best way to determine where to apply 
  resources to create that equity.   By  providing what can be determine as effective and actionable data to the correct customers, in easily understable and digestible ways we can in turn provide that equity with 
  empirical proof.

3. Where and how do you feel equity and community engagement could be addressed more deeply in education data collection and reporting?
 I have always felt that people respond better when they see the benefits of their participation.  For example I recently led a team to develope  a new student survey at UWT.   The main focus was
 that instead of just adding a new survey to the stack of surveys students have to take on campus, that the results we find would be distributed back to the faculty, staff, and students, with
 actionable observations we can work towards.   Participation in just the second run is over 93% which is the highest survey participation we have on campus.  In summation if we return actual results
 for the time put in by the constituants you'll be more likely to get more participation and thus more equity and community engagement

