6. When creating a data display for someone else, what are the common questions you would ask them before starting work?
 I take a very elementary (no pun intended) approach to accessing the steps needed to create a visualization.  Who What When Where and Why.  
 Who is the visualization for (Audience)?
 What are we trying to show in this visualization (Scope)?
 When do you need the visualization by? 
 Where are we planning on housing the visualization?
 Why are we creating the visualization?

7.  Can you give an example of how you work with colleagues from different teams, offices, or agencies? What do you do to ensure successful collaboration?
 With the handoff in higher education from Admissions to Enrollment it has always been vital to work with multiple teams from multiple departments.  Each department needing
 varying data points for varying reasons, but both always having the goal of serving the students.   For example I'll go back to the New Student survey I spoke of earlier.  Admissions had questions 
 regarding why students came to UWT where as  Enrollment wanted to know what we as a campus can provide to keep them at UWT, students wanted a suvey that wasn't 100 pages long.  The best way I've found
 to create successful collaboration is to remind everyone we're on the same team and ensure that everyone feels heard.  I also find that providing alternatives to why X doesn't work with Y is another
 very powerful tool.  In the survey example it was a lot of "well this question is already over here" why don't we just pull that into our analysis and work with it on our end.  

